{"paragraphs":[{"cues":[{"time":0,"text":"So anyway, who am I?"},{"time":1000,"text":"I usually say to people, when they say, \"What do you do?\""},{"time":4000,"text":"I say, \"I do hardware,\""},{"time":6000,"text":"because it sort of conveniently encompasses everything I do."},{"time":8000,"text":"And I recently said that to a venture capitalist casually at some"},{"time":12000,"text":"Valley event, to which he replied, \"How quaint.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":15000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":17000,"text":"And I sort of really was dumbstruck."},{"time":20000,"text":"And I really should have said something smart."},{"time":22000,"text":"And now I've had a little bit of time to think about it,"},{"time":27000,"text":"I would have said, \"Well, you know,"},{"time":29000,"text":"if we look at the next 100 years"},{"time":31000,"text":"and we've seen all these problems in the last few days,"},{"time":33000,"text":"most of the big issues -- clean water, clean energy --"},{"time":36000,"text":"and they're interchangeable in some respects --"},{"time":38000,"text":"and cleaner, more functional materials --"},{"time":40000,"text":"they all look to me to be hardware problems."},{"time":43000,"text":"This doesn't mean we should ignore software,"},{"time":45000,"text":"or information, or computation.\""},{"time":47000,"text":"And that's in fact probably what I'm going to try and tell you about."}]},{"cues":[{"time":50000,"text":"So, this talk is going to be about how do we make things"},{"time":53000,"text":"and what are the new ways that we're going to make things in the future."},{"time":58000,"text":"Now, TED sends you a lot of spam if you're a speaker"},{"time":63000,"text":"about \"do this, do that\" and you fill out all these forms,"},{"time":65000,"text":"and you don't actually know how they're going to describe you,"},{"time":68000,"text":"and it flashed across my desk that they were going to introduce me as a futurist."},{"time":71000,"text":"And I've always been nervous about the term \"futurist,\""},{"time":73000,"text":"because you seem doomed to failure because you can't really predict it."},{"time":76000,"text":"And I was laughing about this with the very smart colleagues I have,"},{"time":79000,"text":"and said, \"You know, well, if I have to talk about the future, what is it?\""},{"time":83000,"text":"And George Homsey, a great guy, said, \"Oh, the future is amazing."},{"time":88000,"text":"It is so much stranger than you think."},{"time":90000,"text":"We're going to reprogram the bacteria in your gut,"},{"time":92000,"text":"and we're going to make your poo smell like peppermint.\""}]},{"cues":[{"time":97000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":99000,"text":"So, you may think that's sort of really crazy,"},{"time":102000,"text":"but there are some pretty amazing things that are happening"},{"time":104000,"text":"that make this possible."},{"time":105000,"text":"So, this isn't my work, but it's work of good friends of mine at MIT."},{"time":109000,"text":"This is called the registry of standard biological parts."},{"time":111000,"text":"This is headed by Drew Endy and Tom Knight"},{"time":113000,"text":"and a few other very, very bright individuals."},{"time":116000,"text":"Basically, what they're doing is looking at biology as a programmable system."},{"time":119000,"text":"Literally, think of proteins as subroutines"},{"time":123000,"text":"that you can string together to execute a program."},{"time":126000,"text":"Now, this is actually becoming such an interesting idea."},{"time":131000,"text":"This is a state diagram. That's an extremely simple computer."}]},{"cues":[{"time":134000,"text":"This one is a two-bit counter."},{"time":136000,"text":"So that's essentially the computational equivalent of two light switches."},{"time":142000,"text":"And this is being built by a group of students at Zurich"},{"time":145000,"text":"for a design competition in biology."},{"time":147000,"text":"And from the results of the same competition last year,"},{"time":150000,"text":"a University of Texas team of students programmed bacteria"},{"time":154000,"text":"so that they can detect light and switch on and off."},{"time":157000,"text":"So this is interesting in the sense that you can now"},{"time":159000,"text":"do \"if-then-for\" statements in materials, in structure."},{"time":164000,"text":"This is a pretty interesting trend,"},{"time":166000,"text":"because we used to live in a world where everyone's said glibly,"},{"time":168000,"text":"\"Form follows function,\" but I think I've sort of grown up in a world"},{"time":172000,"text":"-- you listened to Neil Gershenfeld yesterday;"},{"time":175000,"text":"I was in a lab associated with his -- where it's really a world"},{"time":179000,"text":"where information defines form and function."}]},{"cues":[{"time":182000,"text":"I spent six years thinking about that,"},{"time":186000,"text":"but to show you the power of art over science --"},{"time":188000,"text":"this is actually one of the cartoons I write. These are called \"HowToons.\""},{"time":191000,"text":"I work with a fabulous illustrator called Nick Dragotta."},{"time":193000,"text":"Took me six years at MIT,"},{"time":195000,"text":"and about that many pages to describe what I was doing,"},{"time":199000,"text":"and it took him one page. And so this is our muse Tucker."},{"time":204000,"text":"He's an interesting little kid -- and his sister, Celine --"},{"time":206000,"text":"and what he's doing here"},{"time":208000,"text":"is observing the self-assembly of his Cheerios in his cereal bowl."},{"time":212000,"text":"And in fact you can program the self-assembly of things,"},{"time":215000,"text":"so he starts chocolate-dipping edges,"},{"time":217000,"text":"changing the hydrophobicity and the hydrophylicity."},{"time":219000,"text":"In theory, if you program those sufficiently,"},{"time":221000,"text":"you should be able to do something pretty interesting"},{"time":223000,"text":"and make a very complex structure."},{"time":225000,"text":"In this case, he's done self-replication of a complex 3D structure."},{"time":230000,"text":"And that's what I thought about for a long time,"},{"time":233000,"text":"because this is how we currently make things."},{"time":235000,"text":"This is a silicon wafer, and essentially"},{"time":237000,"text":"that's just a whole bunch of layers of two-dimensional stuff, sort of layered up."},{"time":241000,"text":"The feature side is -- you know, people will say,"},{"time":243000,"text":"[unclear] down around about 65 nanometers now."}]},{"cues":[{"time":245000,"text":"On the right, that's a radiolara."},{"time":247000,"text":"That's a unicellular organism ubiquitous in the oceans."},{"time":250000,"text":"And that has feature sizes down to about 20 nanometers,"},{"time":254000,"text":"and it's a complex 3D structure."},{"time":256000,"text":"We could do a lot more with computers and things generally"},{"time":260000,"text":"if we knew how to build things this way."},{"time":263000,"text":"The secret to biology is, it builds computation"},{"time":266000,"text":"into the way it makes things. So this little thing here, polymerase,"},{"time":269000,"text":"is essentially a supercomputer designed for replicating DNA."},{"time":274000,"text":"And the ribosome here is another little computer"},{"time":277000,"text":"that helps in the translation of the proteins."},{"time":279000,"text":"I thought about this"},{"time":280000,"text":"in the sense that it's great to build in biological materials,"},{"time":283000,"text":"but can we do similar things?"},{"time":285000,"text":"Can we get self-replicating-type behavior?"},{"time":287000,"text":"Can we get complex 3D structure automatically assembling"},{"time":291000,"text":"in inorganic systems?"},{"time":293000,"text":"Because there are some advantages to inorganic systems,"},{"time":295000,"text":"like higher speed semiconductors, etc."}]},{"cues":[{"time":297000,"text":"So, this is some of my work"},{"time":299000,"text":"on how do you do an autonomously self-replicating system."},{"time":305000,"text":"And this is sort of Babbage's revenge."},{"time":307000,"text":"These are little mechanical computers."},{"time":308000,"text":"These are five-state state machines."},{"time":311000,"text":"So, that's about three light switches lined up."},{"time":314000,"text":"In a neutral state, they won't bind at all."},{"time":316000,"text":"Now, if I make a string of these, a bit string,"},{"time":320000,"text":"they will be able to replicate."},{"time":322000,"text":"So we start with white, blue, blue, white."},{"time":323000,"text":"That encodes; that will now copy. From one comes two,"},{"time":329000,"text":"and then from two comes three."},{"time":331000,"text":"And so you've got this sort of replicating system."},{"time":335000,"text":"It was work actually by Lionel Penrose,"},{"time":337000,"text":"father of Roger Penrose, the tiles guy."},{"time":340000,"text":"He did a lot of this work in the '60s,"},{"time":342000,"text":"and so a lot of this logic theory lay fallow"},{"time":344000,"text":"as we went down the digital computer revolution, but it's now coming back."}]},{"cues":[{"time":347000,"text":"So now I'm going to show you the hands-free, autonomous self-replication."},{"time":351000,"text":"So we've tracked in the video the input string,"},{"time":353000,"text":"which was green, green, yellow, yellow, green."},{"time":355000,"text":"We set them off on this air hockey table."},{"time":359000,"text":"You know, high science uses air hockey tables --"}]},{"cues":[{"time":361000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":362000,"text":"-- and if you watch this thing long enough you get dizzy,"},{"time":364000,"text":"but what you're actually seeing is copies of that original string"},{"time":367000,"text":"emerging from the parts bin that you have here."},{"time":370000,"text":"So we've got autonomous replication of bit strings."},{"time":375000,"text":"So, why would you want to replicate bit strings?"},{"time":378000,"text":"Well, it turns out biology has this other very interesting meme,"},{"time":381000,"text":"that you can take a linear string, which is a convenient thing to copy,"},{"time":384000,"text":"and you can fold that into an arbitrarily complex 3D structure."},{"time":388000,"text":"So I was trying to, you know, take the engineer's version:"},{"time":391000,"text":"Can we build a mechanical system in inorganic materials"},{"time":394000,"text":"that will do the same thing?"}]},{"cues":[{"time":395000,"text":"So what I'm showing you here is that we can make a 2D shape --"},{"time":400000,"text":"the B -- assemble from a string of components"},{"time":404000,"text":"that follow extremely simple rules."},{"time":406000,"text":"And the whole point of going with the extremely simple rules here,"},{"time":409000,"text":"and the incredibly simple state machines in the previous design,"},{"time":412000,"text":"was that you don't need digital logic to do computation."},{"time":415000,"text":"And that way you can scale things much smaller than microchips."},{"time":419000,"text":"So you can literally use these as the tiny components in the assembly process."}]},{"cues":[{"time":423000,"text":"So, Neil Gershenfeld showed you this video on Wednesday, I believe,"},{"time":428000,"text":"but I'll show you again."},{"time":430000,"text":"This is literally the colored sequence of those tiles."},{"time":433000,"text":"Each different color has a different magnetic polarity,"},{"time":436000,"text":"and the sequence is uniquely specifying the structure that is coming out."},{"time":441000,"text":"Now, hopefully, those of you who know anything about graph theory"},{"time":444000,"text":"can look at that, and that will satisfy you"},{"time":446000,"text":"that that can also do arbitrary 3D structure,"},{"time":449000,"text":"and in fact, you know, I can now take a dog, carve it up"},{"time":454000,"text":"and then reassemble it so it's a linear string"},{"time":456000,"text":"that will fold from a sequence. And now"},{"time":458000,"text":"I can actually define that three-dimensional object as a sequence of bits."},{"time":465000,"text":"So, you know, it's a pretty interesting world"},{"time":468000,"text":"when you start looking at the world a little bit differently."},{"time":470000,"text":"And the universe is now a compiler."},{"time":473000,"text":"And so I'm thinking about, you know, what are the programs"},{"time":475000,"text":"for programming the physical universe?"},{"time":478000,"text":"And how do we think about materials and structure,"},{"time":481000,"text":"sort of as an information and computation problem?"},{"time":484000,"text":"Not just where you attach a micro-controller to the end point,"},{"time":487000,"text":"but that the structure and the mechanisms are the logic, are the computers."}]},{"cues":[{"time":492000,"text":"Having totally absorbed this philosophy,"},{"time":497000,"text":"I started looking at a lot of problems a little differently."},{"time":500000,"text":"With the universe as a computer,"},{"time":501000,"text":"you can look at this droplet of water"},{"time":503000,"text":"as having performed the computations."},{"time":505000,"text":"You set a couple of boundary conditions, like gravity,"},{"time":507000,"text":"the surface tension, density, etc., and then you press \"execute,\""},{"time":511000,"text":"and magically, the universe produces you a perfect ball lens."},{"time":516000,"text":"So, this actually applied to the problem"},{"time":518000,"text":"of -- so there's a half a billion to a billion people in the world"},{"time":521000,"text":"don't have access to cheap eyeglasses."},{"time":523000,"text":"So can you make a machine"},{"time":525000,"text":"that could make any prescription lens very quickly on site?"},{"time":529000,"text":"This is a machine where you literally define a boundary condition."},{"time":533000,"text":"If it's circular, you make a spherical lens."},{"time":536000,"text":"If it's elliptical, you can make an astigmatic lens."},{"time":539000,"text":"You then put a membrane on that and you apply pressure --"},{"time":542000,"text":"so that's part of the extra program."},{"time":544000,"text":"And literally with only those two inputs --"},{"time":547000,"text":"so, the shape of your boundary condition and the pressure --"},{"time":549000,"text":"you can define an infinite number of lenses"},{"time":551000,"text":"that cover the range of human refractive error,"},{"time":553000,"text":"from minus 12 to plus eight diopters, up to four diopters of cylinder."},{"time":558000,"text":"And then literally, you now pour on a monomer."},{"time":561000,"text":"You know, I'll do a Julia Childs here."},{"time":564000,"text":"This is three minutes of UV light."},{"time":567000,"text":"And you reverse the pressure on your membrane"},{"time":570000,"text":"once you've cooked it. Pop it out."},{"time":573000,"text":"I've seen this video, but I still don't know if it's going to end right."}]},{"cues":[{"time":576000,"text":"(Laughter)"}]},{"cues":[{"time":579000,"text":"So you reverse this. This is a very old movie,"},{"time":581000,"text":"so with the new prototypes, actually both surfaces are flexible,"},{"time":585000,"text":"but this will show you the point."},{"time":587000,"text":"Now you've finished the lens, you literally pop it out."},{"time":589000,"text":"That's next year's Yves Klein, you know, eyeglasses shape."},{"time":596000,"text":"And you can see that that has a mild prescription of about minus two diopters."},{"time":599000,"text":"And as I rotate it against this side shot, you'll see that that has cylinder,"},{"time":603000,"text":"and that was programmed in --"},{"time":604000,"text":"literally into the physics of the system."},{"time":608000,"text":"So, this sort of thinking about structure as computation"},{"time":611000,"text":"and structure as information leads to other things, like this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":616000,"text":"This is something that my people at SQUID Labs"},{"time":619000,"text":"are working on at the moment, called \"electronic rope.\""},{"time":621000,"text":"So literally, you think about a rope. It has very complex structure in the weave."},{"time":625000,"text":"And under no load, it's one structure."},{"time":627000,"text":"Under a different load, it's a different structure. And you can actually exploit that"},{"time":630000,"text":"by putting in a very small number of"},{"time":632000,"text":"conducting fibers to actually make it a sensor."},{"time":634000,"text":"So this is now a rope that knows the load on the rope"},{"time":637000,"text":"at any particular point in the rope."},{"time":639000,"text":"Just by thinking about the physics of the world,"},{"time":642000,"text":"materials as the computer,"},{"time":644000,"text":"you can start to do things like this."}]},{"cues":[{"time":647000,"text":"I'm going to segue a little here."},{"time":650000,"text":"I guess I'm just going to casually tell you the types of things"},{"time":652000,"text":"that I think about with this."},{"time":653000,"text":"One thing I'm really interested about this right now is, how,"},{"time":657000,"text":"if you're really taking this view of the universe as a computer,"},{"time":661000,"text":"how do we make things in a very general sense,"},{"time":663000,"text":"and how might we share the way we make things in a general sense"},{"time":667000,"text":"the same way you share open source hardware?"},{"time":670000,"text":"And a lot of talks here have espoused the benefits"},{"time":673000,"text":"of having lots of people look at problems,"},{"time":675000,"text":"share the information and work on those things together."},{"time":678000,"text":"So, a convenient thing about being a human is you move in linear time,"},{"time":681000,"text":"and unless Lisa Randall changes that,"},{"time":683000,"text":"we'll continue to move in linear time."},{"time":686000,"text":"So that means anything you do, or anything you make,"},{"time":688000,"text":"you produce a sequence of steps --"},{"time":690000,"text":"and I think Lego in the '70s nailed this,"},{"time":693000,"text":"and they did it most elegantly."},{"time":694000,"text":"But they can show you how to build things in sequence."},{"time":698000,"text":"So, I'm thinking about, how can we generalize"},{"time":701000,"text":"the way we make all sorts of things,"},{"time":703000,"text":"so you end up with this sort of guy, right?"},{"time":705000,"text":"And I think this applies across a very broad -- sort of, a lot of concepts."}]},{"cues":[{"time":710000,"text":"You know, Cameron Sinclair yesterday said,"},{"time":712000,"text":"\"How do I get everyone to collaborate on design"},{"time":714000,"text":"globally to do housing for humanity?\""},{"time":717000,"text":"And if you've seen Amy Smith,"},{"time":719000,"text":"she talks about how you get students at MIT"},{"time":723000,"text":"to work with communities in Haiti."},{"time":725000,"text":"And I think we have to sort of redefine and rethink"},{"time":727000,"text":"how we define structure and materials and assembly things,"},{"time":731000,"text":"so that we can really share the information"},{"time":733000,"text":"on how you do those things in a more profound way"},{"time":735000,"text":"and build on each other's source code for structure."},{"time":738000,"text":"I don't know exactly how to do this yet,"},{"time":739000,"text":"but, you know, it's something being actively thought about."}]},{"cues":[{"time":744000,"text":"So, you know, that leads to questions"},{"time":746000,"text":"like, is this a compiler? Is this a sub-routine?"},{"time":750000,"text":"Interesting things like that."},{"time":751000,"text":"Maybe I'm getting a little too abstract, but you know,"},{"time":754000,"text":"this is the sort of -- returning to our comic characters --"},{"time":757000,"text":"this is sort of the universe, or a different universe view,"},{"time":759000,"text":"that I think is going to be very prevalent in the future --"},{"time":761000,"text":"from biotech to materials assembly. It was great to hear Bill Joy."},{"time":764000,"text":"They're starting to invest in materials science,"},{"time":767000,"text":"but these are the new things in materials science."},{"time":769000,"text":"How do we put real information and real structure into new ideas,"},{"time":773000,"text":"and see the world in a different way? And it's not going to be binary code"},{"time":776000,"text":"that defines the computers of the universe --"},{"time":778000,"text":"it's sort of an analog computer."},{"time":780000,"text":"But it's definitely an interesting new worldview."}]},{"cues":[{"time":785000,"text":"I've gone too far. So that sounds like it's it."},{"time":788000,"text":"I've probably got a couple of minutes of questions,"},{"time":790000,"text":"or I can show -- I think they also said that I do extreme stuff"},{"time":794000,"text":"in the introduction, so I may have to explain that."},{"time":798000,"text":"So maybe I'll do that with this short video."}]},{"cues":[{"time":801000,"text":"So this is actually a 3,000-square-foot kite,"},{"time":807000,"text":"which also happens to be a minimal energy surface."},{"time":809000,"text":"So returning to the droplet, again,"},{"time":811000,"text":"thinking about the universe in a new way."},{"time":813000,"text":"This is a kite designed by a guy called Dave Kulp."},{"time":815000,"text":"And why do you want a 3,000-square-foot kite?"},{"time":817000,"text":"So that's a kite the size of your house."},{"time":819000,"text":"And so you want that to tow boats very fast."},{"time":823000,"text":"So I've been working on this a little, also,"},{"time":826000,"text":"with a couple of other guys."},{"time":828000,"text":"But, you know, this is another way to look at the --"},{"time":830000,"text":"if you abstract again,"},{"time":832000,"text":"this is a structure that is defined by the physics of the universe."},{"time":836000,"text":"You could just hang it as a bed sheet,"},{"time":837000,"text":"but again, the computation of all the physics"},{"time":839000,"text":"gives you the aerodynamic shape."},{"time":841000,"text":"And so you can actually sort of almost double your boat speed"},{"time":844000,"text":"with systems like that. So that's sort of another interesting aspect of the future."}]},{"cues":[{"time":851000,"text":"(Applause)"}]}]}